</media>
<para id="fs-idm9922432">(a) What is the maximum number of electrons contained in an orbital of type (x)? Of type (y)? Of type (z)?</para>
<para id="fs-idm66251616">(b) How many orbitals of type (x) are found in a shell with <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> = 2? How many of type (y)? How many of type (z)?</para>
<para id="fs-idm95832304">(c) Write a set of quantum numbers for an electron in an orbital of type (x) in a shell with <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> = 4. Of an orbital of type (y) in a shell with <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> = 2. Of an orbital of type (z) in a shell with <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> = 3.</para>
<para id="fs-idm165503392">(d) What is the smallest possible <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> value for an orbital of type (x)? Of type (y)? Of type (z)?</para>
<para id="fs-idm63155984">(e) What are the possible <emphasis effect="italics">l</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">m<sub>l</sub></emphasis> values for an orbital of type (x)? Of type (y)? Of type (z)?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idm82172944">
<para id="fs-idm90450992">(a) x. 2, y. 2, z. 2; (b) x. 1, y. 3, z. 0; (c) x. 4 0 0 <m:math><m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> y. 2 1 0 <m:math><m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> z. 3 2 0 <m:math><m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:mo>;</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> (d) x. 1, y. 2, z. 3; (e) x. <emphasis effect="italics">l</emphasis> = 0, <emphasis effect="italics">m<sub>l</sub></emphasis> = 0, y. <emphasis effect="italics">l</emphasis> = 1, <emphasis effect="italics">m<sub>l</sub> =</emphasis> –1, 0, or <emphasis effect="italics">+</emphasis>1, z. <emphasis effect="italics">l</emphasis> = 2, <emphasis effect="italics">m<sub>l</sub></emphasis> = –2, –1, 0, +1, +2</para></solution></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm165892704"><problem id="fs-idm152067344">
<para id="fs-idp1974272">State the Heisenberg uncertainty principle. Describe briefly what the principle implies.</para></problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm130545344"><problem id="fs-idm10062944">
<para id="fs-idm159667904">How many electrons could be held in the second shell of an atom if the spin quantum number <emphasis effect="italics">m<sub>s</sub></emphasis> could have three values instead of just two? (Hint: Consider the Pauli exclusion principle.)</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idm164499408">
<para id="fs-idm128894672">12</para></solution></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm68696640"><problem id="fs-idm10527280">
<para id="fs-idm167401120">Which of the following equations describe particle-like behavior? Which describe wavelike behavior? Do any involve both types of behavior? Describe the reasons for your choices.</para>
<para id="fs-idp41728">(a) <emphasis effect="italics">c</emphasis> = <emphasis effect="italics">λν</emphasis></para>
<para id="fs-idm177928192">(b) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>ν</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></para>
<para id="fs-idm133326496">(c) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>Z</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></para>
<para id="fs-idm140528512">(d) <emphasis effect="italics">E = hν</emphasis></para>
<para id="fs-idm152486448">(e) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>λ</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mfrac><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mi>ν</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></para></problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm24126560"><problem id="fs-idm145952864">
